metadata.name: little god #125
metadata.description:
All of our strong emotions, feelings and experiences come from childhood. Sincere happiness or frightening cruelty is primarily inherent in children, so they learn about the world. When we were children, we first hurt someone, first burst into tears from resentment, learned what is good and what is bad. 
Our parents did not answer our questions, either because they did not know the answer or because they thought we were too young. We learned to look for the answers ourselves. Whoever says that children don't understand is a fool. They do understand, but they do it in their own way. The world as seen through the eyes of a child is not like the world as seen through the eyes of an adult. It is often not built on the laws of physics or the laws of the marketplace. In a child's world or universe, the moon is just a little light in the sky, and the next street is already a different country. Their world is built on speculation and magical theories. Unfortunately, a child's world is not eternal. As they grow up, the "real" life, the life of adults, pokes into them like a sharp needle over and over again. 
There is something incredibly tragic about this time gap between child and adult. It is this period that I wanted to trace in my work. As teenagers, it is as if we are between two trains, we are no longer children, but we are not yet adults. We get to know ourselves, we test our strength and readiness to exist in the "real" world. We are trying to find our place in the unfriendly world of adults, but we are also not ready to let go of the magic of childhood. It confuses, torments, and frustrates us. But it is a necessary and unavoidable tragedy. 

Code by PureSpider

metadata.name: One Eleven (are Better Than Thirty) #108
metadata.description:
One Eleven (are Better Than Thirty), is the fourth installment of One Eleven, a periodical experiment.

Even though Andy Warhols work is not cc0, the Mona Lisa is. So yes, this is inspired, heavily, by Andy Warhol, most notably the piece Thirty are Better Than One, but uses no component of it. Let’s call it an homage. We also feel that if Andy were alive today, they would embrace cc0. Art is just about fame and exposure anyways, right?

And yes, initially we wanted to make a grid that had exactly 111 Mona Lisas on it, but tbh, it looked terrible. They were too small, and the iterations were too same-y. So, instead, each iteration of this will have 111 pages, each with varying amounts of Mona Lisas. You just click the art and a new page appears. 111 for each one minted. Then it loops back around.

So, really, this collection gives you 111 pieces for the price of 1, which is free. Pretty good deal.

How do you get on the list? Read below:

Collectors of the genesis One Eleven (#12743) are on the allow list for all One Eleven collections, this one included. A bit before minting is enabled, the list will be updated granting one reserve for each iteration held. So, buy one before this drops. Any procured after the scheduled release time will not get you on the list, but will be considered once the reserves are lifted. Reserves will be lifted after 111 hours, give or take.

As a bonus, whoever holds One Eleven #1 will receive #1 of this collection as an airdrop. The project will be disabled until that happens, but should occur right around the scheduled time.

Half of the royalties for all One Eleven collections will be shared with the minter.

This collection uses the One Eleven SDK, which makes embedding One Eleven into FXHash collections very simple. You can use it if you like for your projects, as it is cc0. Talk to us on twitter if you'd like to release it as a collab.

More info: an0n.wtf/sdk

I'm sorry this is so complicated. When it started, it seemed simpler.

metadata.name: Stones and Sticks #34
metadata.description:
In this project I explore the technique for creating figures, lights, and shades by only using the line primitive. I imagine a primitive world, a distant planet where life can begin again or has just been swept away by some deadly wind. Stones and sticks the only means for building and creating useful tools, just like in this computer-generated image.
-	Hit ‘s’ to save a hi res (5683x3072) png file
-	Dark, Light and Gold modes

metadata.name: Stack of Shapes #81
metadata.description:
Inspired by sketches I'd draw in my college notebook during class. This piece uses a hand-drawn stroke style to draw a stack of overlapping shapes. Look closely and see that the lines are made of thousands of tiny dots. Iterations vary by color scheme, background color, line thickness, density, and more, with a small chance of using a rainbow color palette.  
  
Press R to re-run the drawing animation; enter to save the image in high quality. Enjoy!

🄷🄰-3
